description.value: As Australia’s largest independent not-for-profit aged care provider, Bolton Clarke is shaping the future of positive ageing. Our homes are welcoming and safe communities where lifestyle, social connection and individual interests are celebrated, and quality care comes from the heart. Located in a heritage listed home with warmth and character, our Calare home provides high-quality aged care in a friendly, secure and comfortable residential environment. Our home provides the peace-of-mind of having a Registered Nurse on duty 24/7. Working together with you and your family, we provide personalised care that responds as needs change, including highly specialised care and dementia support, with wellness programs created around your preferences. There are many contemporary and warm spaces to relax and enjoy community life at Calare.

description.value:
At Calvary, we are committed to holistic, resident focused care. We have created a home environment, which supports your independence. By taking the time to get to know you and understand your medical concerns, we can meet your physical, social, emotional and spiritual needs. Our highly trained and attentive team ensure all residents are cared for with integrity and respect. 
Calvary Muswellbrook Retirement Community offers permanent and respite accommodation to 65 residents in single or companion rooms each with a private ensuite, air-conditioning with temperature control, plus flat screen televisions.
Cafe, Gym, Wellness Centre, Community Gardens, BBQ areas, Children's Play ground
All meals prepared and cooked onsite, hairdressing salon, Sitting rooms with tea and coffee facilities, Entertainment by local groups and schools, bus trips and social outings, Internet access, Religious services provided and Palliative care

For more information, please visit our website

past.decision_details:
1.    The Approved Provider is not eligible to receive Commonwealth subsidies for any new care recipients at the service for a period of six (6) months.
2.    Revocation of Approved Provider status, unless the following actions are undertaken:
       a)    an Adviser is appointed by the Approved Provider for a period of six (6) months, at its expense, to assist the Approved Provider to comply with its responsibilities in relation to care and services;
       b)    an Administrator is appointed by the Approved Provider for a period of six (6) months, at its expense, to assist with responsibilities in relation to governance and business operations; and
       (c)   the Approved Provider provides relevant training within six (6) months, at its expense, for its officers, employees and agents at the Service and to demonstrate that they have provided this training.
3.    Vary conditions to which the allocation of places are subject by requiring the provider to have the appropriate number of skilled and qualified staff in this service to ensure that services are delivered in accordance with the Accreditation Standards.
4.    Suspend the allocation of all vacant places and will continue to take effect progressively at the specified services when each allocation place becomes vacant.
5.    Revoke the vacant places if the service is closed.

This service has been given a Direction to make improvements to compliance issues.About the Commission

The Aged Care Quality and Safety Commission (the Commission) has powers under the Aged Care Act and Commission Act to monitor aged care services provided by Approved Providers. The Commission Act allows the Commission to take action when an Approved Provider of aged care services is not meeting its aged care responsibilities at one of its services.

Current compliance issues

This Approved Provider has been given a Direction to revise its Plan for Continuous Improvement for this service.  

The Direction requires the Approved Provider to revise the Plan for Continuous Improvement for this service. This plan must set out how it will:

1) make improvements at the service to ensure the Aged Care Quality Standards are met,

2) assess the care it provides at the service against those Standards, and

3) monitor and improve the quality of care and services as measured against those Standards.

The Aged Care Quality Standards outline how aged care services can provide safe, effective quality care.

The Commission has found that the service has not met 2 out of 42 requirements of the Aged Care Quality Standards. This includes requirements relating to the following Standards:

  • Standard 2 – Ongoing assessment and planning with consumers

 

  • Standard 8 – Organisational governance

Please select a Standard to read more about it on the Commission’s website.
